      Text:
        m_Untranslated: "We'll now cover indirect lighting sampling issues between
          probes having different spacing distances, also called <b>Subdivision Levels.</b>
          \n\nProbes are placed automatically using the <b>Min and Max Probe Spacing</b>
          properties in the <i>Lighting</i> window, under the Probe Volumes tab, 
          depending on the geometrical complexity. In this particular Scene, the
          spacing between Probes will fluctuate between different <b>Subdivision
          Levels</b> at 0.6 m, 1.8 m and 5.4 m. Empty areas may receive fewer probes,
          whereas geometrically dense areas may have more probes. \n\nWhile it may
          be necessary to reduce the total number of probes in the scene by increasing
          the <b>Probe Spacing</b> properties, some unwanted lighting seams may appear
          when sampling happens between different <b>Subdivision Levels,</b> as seen
          in the image above.\n\nTo prevent these unwanted indirect lighting seams
          in this scenario, we can use the <b>Sampling Noise</b> feature in the Volume
          system, in conjunction with <b>Temporal Anti Aliasing.</b>\n\n\nTo reproduce
          the artifact seen in the image above, follow these steps:\n\n1. Add a Cube
          at <b>X:5 Y:5.5 Z:0</b>\n\n2. In the <i>Hierarchy</i> window, select <b>Lighting</b>
          > <b>Volumes</b> > <b>Volume Room 1.</b>\n\n3. In the <i>Inspector</i>
          window, under <b>Probe Volume Options,</b> set the <b>Sampling Noise</b>
          to <b>0.</b> The indirect lighting seam will become obvious. As you can
          see, this feature is fully real-time, therefore it does not require the
          rebaking of the lighting.\n\nIf you do not see the <b>Sampling Noise</b>
          property in the <i>Inspector,</i> click the 3-dots menu on the Probe Volumes
          Options and enable \"Show Additional Properties\".\n\n4. Set the <b>Sampling
          Noise</b> back to <b>0.45.</b>"
